## PowerShell Automation

### User Creation Script

```powershell
Import-Module ActiveDirectory

New-ADUser `
-Name "John Doe" `
-GivenName "John" `
-Surname "Doe" `
-SamAccountName "jdoe" `
-UserPrincipalName "jdoe@company.local" `
-Path "OU=Users,DC=company,DC=local" `
-Enabled $true `
-AccountPassword (ConvertTo-SecureString "P@ssw0rd123!" -AsPlainText -Force)
Replication & Health Validation
Active Directory Replication Checks
repadmin /replsummary
dcdiag /v
Get-ADReplicationFailure -Scope Site
SYSVOL Validation
net share
dfsrmig /getmigrationstate
Get-Service DFSR
Security Hardening

Implemented enterprise security controls:

Microsoft Defender for Endpoint policies
Attack Surface Reduction (ASR) rules
SMB protocol hardening
RDP access restrictions
PowerShell logging and transcription enabled
Credential protection (LSA / Credential Guard)
Windows Firewall enforcement
Advanced audit policy configuration
Challenges Encountered
DFSR SYSVOL Replication Failure

A replication failure occurred due to DFSR state inconsistency and replication topology mismatch between domain controllers.

Resolution Steps
Verified Active Directory replication integrity first
Analyzed DFSR event logs for root cause indicators
Forced non-authoritative SYSVOL synchronization
Rebuilt DFSR replication membership configuration
Confirmed SYSVOL health across all domain controllers
Lessons Learned
DNS misconfiguration can silently break Active Directory environments
DFSR is highly sensitive to state corruption and requires strict recovery procedures
PowerShell automation reduces operational errors and improves efficiency
Replication monitoring is critical in multi-domain-controller environments
Disaster recovery must be validated through real failure simulation
